252
00:22:26,333 --> 00:22:28,125
and we're not actually together,

253
00:22:29,125 --> 00:22:31,083
we kind of are in a way, you know?

254
00:22:33,000 --> 00:22:38,583
Like, we're both underneath
the same sky, so…

255
00:22:40,958 --> 00:22:42,166
we're kind of together.

256
00:22:47,250 --> 00:22:48,541
One. Head under.

257
00:22:48,625 --> 00:22:50,000
-[speaks indistinctly]
-Two.

258
00:22:50,083 --> 00:22:51,333
Three.

259
00:22:51,416 --> 00:22:52,625
Four.

260
00:22:52,708 --> 00:22:53,583
Four and a half…

261
00:22:53,666 --> 00:22:54,750
-Stop, stop.
-What?

262
00:22:54,833 --> 00:22:57,833
-[kids shouting indistinctly, playing]
-[somber music continues]

263
00:23:01,208 --> 00:23:02,375
[Sophie] Can we do that?

264
00:23:06,541 --> 00:23:07,541
[Calum] Hmm?

265
00:23:11,166 --> 00:23:12,583
You're too young, poppet.

266
00:23:20,708 --> 00:23:21,708
[music fades]

267
00:23:42,833 --> 00:23:46,333
-[shower running]
-[Sophie] Ladies and gentlemen,

268
00:23:46,416 --> 00:23:51,666
the marvelous, wonderful, amazing,
one-armed Calum Aaron Patterson.

269
00:23:52,625 --> 00:23:57,625
Getting ready to see
the evening entertainment.

270
00:23:58,833 --> 00:23:59,833
And…

271
00:24:01,291 --> 00:24:02,291
We'll see…

272
00:24:03,375 --> 00:24:04,750
[squealing] Torremolinos!

273
00:24:05,666 --> 00:24:06,875
[Calum] You okay, Soph?

274
00:24:11,291 --> 00:24:14,291
-[pop song playing on speakers]
-[indistinct chatter]

275
00:24:21,166 --> 00:24:23,208
[Sophie] You've not mentioned Claire.

276
00:24:23,291 --> 00:24:24,958
Hmm? Um…

277
00:24:27,750 --> 00:24:29,958
Remember she had a boyfriend
when we first met?

278
00:24:30,583 --> 00:24:31,583
Yup.

279
00:24:32,333 --> 00:24:33,958
I was like, "Who's that on the phone?"

280
00:24:34,041 --> 00:24:37,750
You were like, "Oh, just this girl I like,
but she's already going out with someone."

281
00:24:37,833 --> 00:24:39,541
Yeah, well, they got back together.

282
00:24:40,208 --> 00:24:42,166
Aw. I liked her.

283
00:24:42,250 --> 00:24:43,750
Mmm-hmm. Me, too.

284
00:24:43,833 --> 00:24:45,916
So, does that mean
you're not gonna open the café?

285
00:24:46,000 --> 00:24:47,000
Café?

286
00:24:47,708 --> 00:24:50,000
Uh, no. Not anymore.

287
00:24:50,083 --> 00:24:53,125
But… I've got this new thing going
with Keith.

288
00:24:54,791 --> 00:24:55,916
What is it?

289
00:24:56,541 --> 00:24:59,833
Well, we're still figuring it out exactly,

290
00:24:59,916 --> 00:25:03,333
but we're thinking of renting a house
a wee bit outside London to work from.

291
00:25:03,416 --> 00:25:05,666
You'd have your own room
for when you come down.

292
00:25:06,958 --> 00:25:09,416
-Yes. Can I paint it yellow?
-Yellow?

293
00:25:10,083 --> 00:25:11,083
Why yellow?

294
00:25:11,833 --> 00:25:13,208
I like the idea of a yellow room,

295
00:25:13,291 --> 00:25:15,541
but Mum doesn't let me
paint my room yellow.

296
00:25:15,625 --> 00:25:16,666
[chuckles]

297
00:25:16,750 --> 00:25:19,041
[sing-song]
You're trying to get me into trouble.

298
00:25:19,500 --> 00:25:20,708
Well, can I, though?

299
00:25:21,666 --> 00:25:22,625
Aye, we'll see.

300
00:25:22,708 --> 00:25:25,291
["Macarena, Bayside Boys Remix"
playing over speakers]

301
00:25:25,375 --> 00:25:28,000
-Right, let's watch this.
-[people cheering, applauding]

302
00:25:33,666 --> 00:25:36,125
-[song continues]
-[people clapping rhythmically]

303
00:25:39,625 --> 00:25:40,625
[people whooping]

304
00:25:44,500 --> 00:25:46,708
♪ When I dance they call me Macarena ♪

305
00:25:46,791 --> 00:25:49,000
♪ And the boys they say
"Que estoy buena" ♪

306
00:25:49,083 --> 00:25:51,416
♪ They all want me, they can't have me ♪

307
00:25:51,500 --> 00:25:53,833
♪ So they all come and dance beside me ♪

308
00:25:53,916 --> 00:25:56,083
♪ Move with me, chant with me ♪

309
00:25:56,166 --> 00:25:58,250
♪ And if you're good
I'll take you home with me ♪

310
00:25:58,333 --> 00:26:00,416
-[song continues playing]
-[indistinct conversation]

311
00:26:01,458 --> 00:26:03,500
[Calum] Soph, did you bring your wallet?

312
00:26:03,583 --> 00:26:04,583
No? No?

313
00:26:05,041 --> 00:26:07,041
Okay. Grab this.

314
00:26:07,666 --> 00:26:09,166
Do not look at him.

315
00:26:09,250 --> 00:26:12,291
When I count to three, we'll throw it
at the stage and leave. Understand?

316
00:26:15,250 --> 00:26:16,583
[Calum shouts indistinctly]

317
00:26:16,666 --> 00:26:21,166
♪ Now don't you worry about my boyfriend
The boy whose name is Vitorino ♪

318
00:26:39,916 --> 00:26:41,000
[Sophie] Did it hurt?

319
00:26:43,875 --> 00:26:44,958
When you fell.

320
00:26:47,208 --> 00:26:49,083
-[Calum] When I broke my wrist?
-Uh-huh.

321
00:26:51,583 --> 00:26:52,416
I don't know.

322
00:26:54,333 --> 00:26:55,625
I don't really remember.

323
00:26:57,041 --> 00:26:59,500
Um, I didn't think it was broken then.

324
00:27:00,333 --> 00:27:01,958
I'd never broken anything before.

325
00:27:03,375 --> 00:27:04,208
[grunts softly]

326
00:27:04,291 --> 00:27:06,166
[Sophie] I've never broken
anything before.

327
00:27:06,250 --> 00:27:07,250
[Calum] Mmm.

328
00:27:13,125 --> 00:27:15,833
-How come you and Mum say, "Love you"?
-What?

329
00:27:16,416 --> 00:27:17,958
Like, on the phone.

330
00:27:18,708 --> 00:27:20,875
You're not together,
so why would you say it?

331
00:27:22,500 --> 00:27:23,500
Well…

332
00:27:24,750 --> 00:27:26,916
Think of all the people you say it to.

333
00:27:27,000 --> 00:27:30,833
Like, your nana, granddad,
uncle, aunties, right?

334
00:27:32,583 --> 00:27:34,250
Yeah, but they're, like, family.

335
00:27:34,333 --> 00:27:35,750
Well, your mother is family.

336
00:27:50,416 --> 00:27:53,541
[Sophie] I remember one time
I asked Mum if she'd phoned you.

337
00:27:53,625 --> 00:27:56,125
-[Calum groans softly]
-And she said that you were engaged.

338
00:27:56,208 --> 00:27:57,958
Like, I didn't know why,

339
00:27:58,041 --> 00:28:00,625
but I thought that meant
that you were getting married,

340
00:28:00,708 --> 00:28:02,208
like, both of youse.

341
00:28:02,291 --> 00:28:06,583
Like, I didn't know if I thought that
about just you or both of you, but…

342
00:28:07,791 --> 00:28:09,583
[Calum grunts, winces]

343
00:28:11,666 --> 00:28:12,666
Isn't that funny?

344
00:28:15,708 --> 00:28:19,041
Well, I didn't know
what it meant at the time.

345
00:28:19,125 --> 00:28:22,458
I didn't know that it meant that you were
just on the phone to somebody else.

346
00:28:25,458 --> 00:28:26,791
I was kind of excited.

347
00:28:28,166 --> 00:28:29,458
About us getting married?

348
00:28:31,791 --> 00:28:33,458
Yeah. I was really young, though.

349
00:28:33,541 --> 00:28:34,541
Like…

350
00:28:35,333 --> 00:28:36,791
I don't know, like, seven.

351
00:28:40,083 --> 00:28:41,625
How are you getting on with the book?

352
00:28:43,083 --> 00:28:44,083
You enjoying it?

353
00:28:46,916 --> 00:28:49,958
Yeah, it's a bit hard
to understand, though.

354
00:28:52,500 --> 00:28:53,583
[Calum] Stick with it.

355
00:28:54,500 --> 00:28:55,958
I think you'll really like it.

356
00:28:56,041 --> 00:28:58,041
[water dripping]

357
00:29:03,458 --> 00:29:06,125
What does "municipal" mean?

358
00:29:06,208 --> 00:29:07,375
[water lapping softly]

359
00:29:12,416 --> 00:29:14,416
[somber music playing]

360
00:29:45,458 --> 00:29:47,041
[Calum] A proper dive, Soph.

361
00:29:47,125 --> 00:29:48,708
[Sophie] I told you, I can't.

362
00:29:48,791 --> 00:29:50,916
-[Calum] You were diving last year.
-No, I wasn't.

363
00:29:51,000 --> 00:29:51,833
[Calum] Here.

364
00:29:57,958 --> 00:29:59,625
-[Sophie] Pass me my mask.
-I did.

365
00:30:00,416 --> 00:30:01,500
[Sophie] What?

366
00:30:01,583 --> 00:30:03,458
[Calum] Come on, Soph,
stop messing around.

367
00:30:03,541 --> 00:30:04,958
[Sophie] I'm not messing around.

368
00:30:08,875 --> 00:30:10,875
[somber music continues]

369
00:30:19,000 --> 00:30:20,000
[music fades]

370
00:30:20,083 --> 00:30:22,625
[man speaking in Spanish]
I don't deserve this.

371
00:30:28,958 --> 00:30:30,958
Shut up, don't be silly.

372
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:48,000
[man and woman laugh]

373
00:30:51,250 --> 00:30:53,875
No, to the right.
You've already applied it there.

374
00:31:07,708 --> 00:31:09,416
You know I didn't see you throw it.

375
00:31:10,458 --> 00:31:11,666
[Calum] Throw what?

376
00:31:11,750 --> 00:31:14,291
The mask. I know it was expensive.

377
00:31:36,333 --> 00:31:37,458
That's okay, darling.

378
00:31:39,583 --> 00:31:42,083
It's fine.
I'm just a little tired today, that's all.

379
00:31:45,875 --> 00:31:47,541
Can you run up and grab the camera?

380
00:31:48,291 --> 00:31:49,291
It's in the bag.

381
00:31:55,625 --> 00:31:56,625
[sighs]

382
00:32:01,708 --> 00:32:02,708
[straining]

383
00:32:05,750 --> 00:32:08,583
[man] Here.
Put that on your foot, then try again.

384
00:32:08,666 --> 00:32:09,583
[Calum] On my foot?

385
00:32:09,666 --> 00:32:11,500
Yeah, put it on.
It's gonna be much easier.

386
00:32:14,666 --> 00:32:16,333
[chuckles]

387
00:32:16,416 --> 00:32:18,625
-You need help?
-Yeah, please. Thanks.

388
00:32:19,750 --> 00:32:20,750
There we go.

389
00:32:21,791 --> 00:32:23,916
-Thank you.
-That's a trick of the trade.

390
00:32:26,916 --> 00:32:28,125
It's not a bad trade.

391
00:32:29,333 --> 00:32:30,458
Nope, not at all.

392
00:32:33,250 --> 00:32:34,916
Is this what you do all year round, then?

393
00:32:35,000 --> 00:32:37,333
You sound like my anneanne,
my mother's mum.

394
00:32:37,416 --> 00:32:38,875
-Your grandma?
-Yeah.

395
00:32:38,958 --> 00:32:41,166
She would prefer that I had a proper job.

396
00:32:41,833 --> 00:32:44,000
-What is your shoe size?
-Uh, ten.

397
00:32:44,708 --> 00:32:47,208
-Ten.
-Forty-four?

398
00:32:47,291 --> 00:32:48,458
-[man] Forty-four.
-Yeah.

399
00:32:49,666 --> 00:32:51,291
-I think these should fit.
-Yeah.

400
00:32:52,791 --> 00:32:55,291
You know, I used to travel a lot.

401
00:32:55,375 --> 00:32:57,666
One season somewhere,
next season somewhere else,

402
00:32:57,750 --> 00:32:59,500
but now I'm here, back home.

403
00:32:59,583 --> 00:33:00,875
And do you miss it?

404
00:33:00,958 --> 00:33:02,541
-Travelling?
-Aye.

405
00:33:02,625 --> 00:33:04,958
Not as much as I was missing home,
to be honest.

406
00:33:05,041 --> 00:33:06,916
And I'm going to have a baby soon.

407
00:33:07,000 --> 00:33:08,625
-[chuckles] Congratulations.
-Yeah.

408
00:33:08,708 --> 00:33:12,166
A few years ago, I thought I would be
at least 40 before all that, but…

409
00:33:16,125 --> 00:33:18,375
[Calum] I can't see myself at 40,
to be honest.

410
00:33:21,125 --> 00:33:22,625
Surprised I made it to 30.

411
00:33:27,833 --> 00:33:28,833
[sighs]

412
00:33:49,250 --> 00:33:53,125
My name is Sophie Lesley Patterson
reporting live from…

413
00:33:55,250 --> 00:33:56,708
I don't know the name of this boat.

414
00:33:56,791 --> 00:33:59,875
Um, but, basically,
I have just went and done

415
00:33:59,958 --> 00:34:05,375
the most amazing thing
in my whole entire life.

416
00:34:05,916 --> 00:34:10,958
So, we went, like, scuba diving thing.

417
00:34:11,041 --> 00:34:13,208
And there was actually, like, a sea horse,

418
00:34:13,291 --> 00:34:17,625
and it wrapped round
my, like, whole finger.

419
00:34:17,708 --> 00:34:22,208
Then when I got out,
there was an… octopus,

420
00:34:22,291 --> 00:34:24,291
and the instructor person…

421
00:34:24,375 --> 00:34:25,208
I don't know.

422
00:34:25,291 --> 00:34:27,458
Like, yeah, instructor put it on…

423
00:34:27,541 --> 00:34:29,541
put an octopus on my head.

424
00:34:29,625 --> 00:34:31,791
A real-life octopus on my head.

425
00:34:33,375 --> 00:34:36,291
Yeah, but right now, Dad…

426
00:34:36,375 --> 00:34:39,333
I mean, Calum Aaron Patterson…

427
00:34:40,250 --> 00:34:45,125
is away on some
scuba diving thing, I think.

428
00:34:45,208 --> 00:34:47,416
I can't remember, but…

429
00:34:48,083 --> 00:34:51,500
Yeah, he doesn't actually have
a diving licence,

430
00:34:51,583 --> 00:34:53,750
'cause he told a porky pie.

431
00:34:53,833 --> 00:34:54,833
[chuckles]

432
00:34:55,416 --> 00:34:56,541
But, yeah.

433
00:34:57,250 --> 00:34:58,416
He'll be fine.

434
00:34:58,500 --> 00:34:59,500
Yeah.

435
00:35:00,083 --> 00:35:01,750
He'll be fine, I'm sure. [chuckles]

436
00:35:02,291 --> 00:35:04,958
But, yeah! Bye-bye. Bye-bye.

437
00:35:05,833 --> 00:35:07,416
Bye-bye. Bye-bye.

438
00:35:07,500 --> 00:35:08,916
Bye-bye. Bye-bye.

439
00:35:15,291 --> 00:35:17,291
[moody music playing]

440
00:35:45,833 --> 00:35:46,833
[music fades]

441
00:35:46,916 --> 00:35:48,916
[people speaking indistinctly]

442
00:35:49,833 --> 00:35:51,625
[paragliding woman screams excitedly]

443
00:35:56,083 --> 00:35:57,333
[paragliding man whooping]

444
00:36:01,500 --> 00:36:02,500
What's that?

445
00:36:05,166 --> 00:36:06,166
What?

446
00:36:09,958 --> 00:36:14,291
Uh, that's just another kind of smoking,
and smoking--

447
00:36:14,375 --> 00:36:17,375
Smoking causes cancer,
and puts tar in your lungs,

448
00:36:17,458 --> 00:36:19,458
and makes your teeth all yellow,

449
00:36:19,541 --> 00:36:22,125
and causes your eyeballs to fall out.

450
00:36:22,208 --> 00:36:23,375
[Calum chuckles softly]

451
00:36:25,041 --> 00:36:26,708
We'll go somewhere else next time.

452
00:36:28,333 --> 00:36:31,291
It's not that bad. When was the last time
you want to see Nana?

453
00:36:34,291 --> 00:36:35,208
Hmm.

454
00:36:43,125 --> 00:36:44,041
Right.

455
00:36:46,083 --> 00:36:47,083
Trouble.

456
00:36:47,791 --> 00:36:49,708
So, watch again, okay?

457
00:36:49,791 --> 00:36:51,458
-Okay. Let's see.
-Okay?

458
00:36:53,708 --> 00:36:55,541
Right, that was a bad start.

459
00:37:05,583 --> 00:37:07,208
When are you back at school?

460
00:37:07,291 --> 00:37:09,583
-Thursday.
-Next week?

461
00:37:09,666 --> 00:37:12,083
-Crazy.
-God, I thought it was a bit later.

462
00:37:14,041 --> 00:37:16,833
-Who's your new teacher?
-Miss Mackel.

463
00:37:17,458 --> 00:37:18,708
Aye, the one from Glasgow?

464
00:37:24,583 --> 00:37:25,666
How'd you know that?

465
00:37:29,166 --> 00:37:30,166
What?

466
00:37:33,833 --> 00:37:35,041
She's pretty.

467
00:37:35,125 --> 00:37:36,250
[laughs]

468
00:37:36,333 --> 00:37:38,791
She's the pretty one from Glasgow.
She's stuck in my head.

469
00:37:38,875 --> 00:37:40,375
Oh, my God, Dad, stop!

470
00:37:40,458 --> 00:37:42,291
-[Calum chuckles] Okay.
-Stop.

471
00:37:43,541 --> 00:37:44,833
Is she supposed to be good?

472
00:37:46,291 --> 00:37:48,291
We done a crossover at the end of term.

473
00:37:48,958 --> 00:37:49,958
Seems all right.

474
00:37:50,458 --> 00:37:51,458
[Calum chuckles]

475
00:37:58,875 --> 00:38:00,875
[indistinct chatter]

476
00:38:03,416 --> 00:38:04,416
[bus honking]

477
00:38:10,458 --> 00:38:16,875
[on speakers] ♪ If all you've got to
Prove today is your innocence… ♪

478
00:38:18,416 --> 00:38:19,875
[automated voice] Insert coin.

479
00:38:24,291 --> 00:38:25,291
[video game trills]

480
00:38:27,625 --> 00:38:29,458
-Insert coin.
-You playing?

481
00:38:29,541 --> 00:38:31,166
[Sophie] Dad's gone to get money.

482
00:38:31,250 --> 00:38:32,500
Here, watch this.

483
00:38:37,166 --> 00:38:39,500
-[automated voice] Insert coin.
-10p.

484
00:38:41,458 --> 00:38:42,458
[coin clatters]

485
00:38:42,541 --> 00:38:44,541
-[Sophie] Got another?
-[chuckles softly]

486
00:38:52,041 --> 00:38:53,291
I'm Michael, by the way.

487
00:38:54,916 --> 00:38:57,750
[Sophie] Well, you better
have been practicing, Michael.

488
00:38:57,833 --> 00:38:59,791
-[Michael] Harsh.
-[video game trilling]

489
00:39:01,625 --> 00:39:04,208
-[Michael] What's your name, then?
-Sophie.

490
00:39:05,791 --> 00:39:07,791
[engines revving in video game]

491
00:39:23,083 --> 00:39:24,166
[tires screeching]

492
00:39:24,250 --> 00:39:26,416
-[automated voice] Game over.
-[Sophie] Are you joking?

493
00:39:26,500 --> 00:39:28,208
-[video game trilling]
-That's 1-1.

494
00:39:28,875 --> 00:39:30,916
I didn't know we were keeping count.

495
00:39:31,000 --> 00:39:32,000
Yes, you did.

496
00:39:34,375 --> 00:39:35,916
♪ You ♪

497
00:39:37,291 --> 00:39:41,750
♪ You've been racing
Through the best days ♪

498
00:39:44,458 --> 00:39:48,500
♪ Space age, road rage, fast lane ♪

499
00:39:48,583 --> 00:39:54,208
♪ And if all you've got to do today ♪

500
00:39:54,291 --> 00:39:57,583
♪ Is find peace of mind ♪

501
00:39:59,458 --> 00:40:04,500
♪ Come here
You can take a piece of mine ♪

502
00:40:04,583 --> 00:40:06,583
[song fades into
somber instrumental music]

503
00:40:08,333 --> 00:40:10,333
-[water lapping softly]
-[insects trilling]

504
00:40:29,000 --> 00:40:30,000
[music fades]

